{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4e3a3ccc-64ff-4b65-9fea-a69d1ae5a0b2","content":"**Use `dotnet-trace`** — it's the easiest purpose-built tool for .NET CPU profiling.\n\n### Quick steps:\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Install (one-time)\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a CPU trace (30 seconds example)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### If you need OS-level detail (drivers, kernel, etc.):\n\nUse **PerfView** directly — it captures ETW events:\n\n```powershell\n# Download from https://github.com/microsoft/perfview/releases\nPerfView.exe collect -Duration:30 -CircularMB:500\n```\n\n### When to pick which:\n\n| Tool | Best for |\n|---|---|\n| `dotnet-trace` | Managed code hot paths, quick & simple |\n| PerfView | Full-stack (managed + native + kernel), GC analysis |\n\nStart with `dotnet-trace` — it's lightweight, doesn't require a reboot, and covers most .NET CPU issues.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b596235f-8e2b-4a40-b740-350555745390","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a general knowledge question — no codebase work needed. I'll give a concise, practical answer.","outputTokens":364,"requestId":"6016:35BDDE:2811FB:2F5B04:69EAC588"},"id":"d34fe703-0f34-4211-9786-f52a2b325169","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:21:22.258Z","parentId":"63e91773-25ef-4b96-a0d4-22fb8b7c7a67"}
